			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">In Chromium Linux, the address space randomisation is currently per-Chromium-instance, because all 
renderer and NaCl processes are forked from a single "zygote" process.  Naturally this will change 
once we fix http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=303.

I'm curious, what systems have per-boot address space randomisation?

BTW, I've been using the term "read sandboxing".  Can we settle on a term?  It's just that it 
makes it easier to search for it.
